+| A-059 | The 006G `ApprovalCase` is a unique pending sanction-submission shell linked one-to-one to its application and appraisal; approval-matrix rule, required/excluded approver snapshots, decision actions, and exception records remain unset/unmodelled until Epic 007 enriches that same row. | Source data-model §15.3 expects a matrix rule and approver snapshots, while API §24.5 permits an exception route to be created or flagged. The selected slice explicitly excludes matrix evaluation/assignment and requires the smallest case persistence, so fabricating approvers or a matrix rule would invent governance facts. | `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §24.5/§25.1-§25.2; `docs/source/data-model.md` §15.2-§15.4; `docs/source/implementation-roadmap.md` §12; `docs/slices/006G-submit-to-sanction.md` | 006G and 007A/007B | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | 007A defines effective rules; 007B must enrich the existing unique 006G case rather than create a second case. |
+| A-060 | Sanction submission changes `application_status` and `appraisal_status` to `submitted_to_sanction_committee` but leaves `LoanApplication.current_stage = credit_assessment` until source governance names the corresponding one-of-six SOP stage value. | Source data-model and auth workflow tables name the submitted status but do not name a separate `current_stage` value for sanction; inventing `sanction`, `approval`, or another stage would create a new persisted vocabulary. | `docs/source/data-model.md` loan-application status/§13.1; `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §20.1; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §24.5 | 006G and Epic 007 | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Epic 007 should set a stage only if a source-backed canonical value is added; historical status facts must not be rewritten. |
